alism. Many of the multiracial family organizations that exist across the United States developed socially, ideologically, and politically during the conservative Reagan years. While members of the Multiracial Movement differ widely in their political views, the concept of multiracialism has been taken up by conservative politicians in ways that are often inimical to the interests of traditionally defined minorities.Contributors look at the Multiracial Movement's voice and at the political controversies that attend the notion of multiracialism in academic and popular literature, internet discourse, census debates, and discourse by and about pop culture celebrities. The work discusses how multiracialism, hybridity, and racial mixing have occurred amidst existing academic discussions of authenticity, community borders, identity politics, the social construction of race, and postmodern fragmentation. How the Multiracial Movement is shaping and transforming collective multiracial identities is also explored.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEthnicityzUnited States. 0aRace awarenesszUnited States. 0aRacially mixed peoplexRace identityzUnited States. 0aRacially mixed peoplezUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aRacismzUnited States. 0aSocial movementszUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aSociology : Ethnicity. 4aSociology : Social Problems. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aChilds, Erica Chito, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDacosta, Kimberly Mcclain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalmage, Heather M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalmage, Heather M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFerber, Abby L., 